[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Developer workflows today are increasingly prompt driven. [music] You prompt an agent, review the output, tweak the prompt, and repeat. As soon as you want to run many agents, automate work, or collaborate as a team, you start hitting the limits of a single laptop.'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s why today we\'re excited to introduce you to Oz. Oz is a new kind of coding agent that can run locally, remotely, or be triggered via SDK. Oz is designed to be fast and simple. In'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'minutes, not hours. You can set up Oz agents in the cloud that can make changes across multiple repos. You can even run them on a schedule or triggered by events. Monitor all your agents from one place right within warp or the new'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Oz web app. And each agent has a sharable session link which is automatically generated on every run. That means with one click, teammates can observe progress, [music]'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'jump into steer, or pick up locally when an agent gets stuck. Oz is consistent across every surface. Launch agents from the CLI, web app, the API, or SDK, or directly inside Warp.'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Yes, it even works on mobile. Automate repeatable tasks. Create custom programmable agents in Oz. Oz uses the skills standard so you can turn your'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'existing agent skills into true agent automations. As agents take on more real work, teams need simple, reliable primitives for running them. Launch, track, collaborate, and audit, all without'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'complexity. Agents are no longer experiments you run on a single machine. They\'re becoming part of how teams actually build software. We are excited for you to try Oz today.'
